\begin_layout Standard
While the predominant view of status in empirical economics remains one
 that is based on hierarchy of ranks (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goldthorpeOccupationalGrading1975,wegener1992prestigeconcepts,goldthorpesociology2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), several attempts have been made in both sociology and economics to view
 status in a more dynamic framework (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "webereconomysociety1925,wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Instead of treating status goals separate from economic goals, the presented
 chapter pins down a specific link between economics and social goals relevant
 for status consumption by allowing an indirect (instrumental) effect of
 status on consumer wealth (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "postlewaite1998socialbasisinterdeppreferences"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The contrast between economic and social goals has received much attention
 in the the sociological literature where several attempts have been made
 to reconcile the subjective aspects of status (the effect of status differences
 on individual behaviour) and its objective aspects (the observed reality
 of status differences).
 A certain dynamism to address the issue has been experimented either within
 an order of hierarchy (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moldovanuselacontestsstatus2007,parsonssystemsocieties1971"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ) or as a conflict among social aggregates (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "webereconomysociety1925"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The current chapter banks a view of status provided by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goode1978celebrationheroes"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 wherein status is necessarily shaped by the institutional nurturing or
 discouragement of certain attributes.
 Given the wide-differences in the level of development that is often observed
 among developing economies (such as Tanzania and Nigeria), the current
 chapter investigates how expenditure towards status could change with rising
 income differences in an environment where both social capital and raw-skills
 have a role to play in the individual's status-influenced economic success.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike the typical attribution of status to exogenous factors such as race
 or caste, the chapter attempts to explain how variation in urban institutions
 influence expenditures such as education that contribute to income mobility
 while also carrying some status value.
 The explanations follow the Weberian framework that contrasts 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Geschellschaft}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{Gemeinschaft}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and has been widely used in both sociology and economics (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "webereconomysociety1925,goode1978celebrationheroes"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The endogenisation of status i.e.
 its explanation in economic terms - as well as the parametrisation of urbanisat
ion is meant to help with the theoretical arguments for how expenditures
 towards status in economies may change as the access to institutions such
 as secondary or tertiary education and income differences change over time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The structural basis for the relation between economic and social goals
 rests upon arguments from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "postlewaite1998socialbasisinterdeppreferences"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 that an economy for status ought to be considered separate from one where
 the consumer utility is maximised.
 As also argued by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "postlewaite1998socialbasisinterdeppreferences"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 , the degree of uncertainty is often an important motivation for the signaling
 in the context of conspicuous consumption.
 The current chapter thus views status competitions as a probabilistic game
 where individuals compete with both raw-talent and acquired-skills (social
 capital) to get promoted from a poor to rich position.
 The winner of the game is promoted to a rich position (or maintains her
 rich position) by having the maximum total score comprising both of raw-talent
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 (uniformly distributed in a population) and social capital 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 (enhanced with expenditure).
 The social-capital 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 that is enhanced through expenditure is also subject to budget constraints
 imposed on the consumer
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We do not view leisure as separate from budget constraints in the model.
 In other words, the leisure relevant for higher stauts is interpreted simply
 as a higher cost for the poorer participant.
 So long as once can view leisure as the amount of money a participant must
 forgo in order to participate in status competition, the leisure differences
 can be also viewed as differences in disposable incomes.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this tournament view of status, the only two types of participants are
 the poor and rich classes so that investments towards status (such as club-memb
ership fees, or higher-education) increase the chances to be promoted.
 Those who don't participate in the tournament certainly suffer with being
 poor, but those who do spend only benefit probabilistically.
 A useful analogy to explain such tournaments are tennis championships -
 where rewards are risky but are not like lotteries where more expenditure
 may linearly increase one's chance to win.
 As with the game of tennis, participants with appropriate raw-talent and
 skills may exist naturally in a population.
 While there exist certain biological characteristics such as strength,
 dexterity, height or psychological abilities (resilience, conscientiousness
 etc.) that help one's tennis, there also exist several characteristics such
 as technique, rankings, knowledge of conventions, racket-customisations
 that are only available at a significant cost to the participant.
 The enhancement of these latter skills (social capital) are what the institutio
nal support discussed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goode1978celebrationheroes"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 are meant to represent.
 As 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goode1978celebrationheroes"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argues, the characteristics of such status games are often made to reward
 curated abilities rather than naturally occurring raw-strengths.
 A significant number of participants may thus never realise their true
 potential unless they spend enough to hone their skills.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using a simple model of uncertainty, the probability to win depends on the
 combined weighted distribution of raw-talent and enhanced-skills.
 Thus a winner of the game is the participant who has the highest combined
 score consisting of raw-talent 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and skills 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 (the latter enhanced with expenditure).
 To arrive the long-term equilibrium condition, we also assume that the
 participants keep the population constant over time and therefore the number
 of rich positions in the population remain fixed in the long-term.
 The rich participants are thus replaced by either a rich or poor participant
 only through a tournament that selects the participant with the highest
 combined score - regardless of their rich or poor background.
 All participants participate in every such tournament so it is possible
 for a rich participant to lose her rich-position and let another participant
 acquire her position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The preferences for all poor participants are the same as are the preferences
 of all the rich participants.
 Having a rich or a poor status by itself only has an indirect effect (through
 higher expenditure or budget) on the chance to be promoted (or maintaining
 one's rich position) - a probability that otherwise depends on the privately
 known ability 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and social-capital 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 All rich participants and all poor participants having the same behaviour
 also means that the privately known attributes 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 are not used by the participant to decide upon the expenditure (effort)
 towards the status game.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the rich and poor participants have disparate incomes 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 (so that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}<y_{2}$
\end_inset

), then the above setup evidently puts the poor participants at a disadvantage
 since they may not afford to pay the costs to enhance their skills (i.e.
 realise the true worth of their skills 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 due to high participation costs).
 However, since both raw-talent 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and skills 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 potentially enhanced by costly institutional support are randomly distributed
 in the population, the competition may never rule out the chance for a
 poor participant to win.
 For the same reason, the returns from investments to enhance one's skills
 may also be diminishing since one cannot beat raw-talent and non enhanced-skill
s after a certain point.
 Considering the weight of raw-talent in the total score as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 we derive long-term equilibrium conditions with a winning probability of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu r_{i}+(1-\mu)s_{i}$
\end_inset

 being the maximum score among participants in a tournament (see Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for details).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to highlight that above status competitions are not meant
 to be population-wide tournaments that involve all participants of a society.
 Instead, the competitions are small-scale with varied locally defined criteria
 that may have multiple stages.
 All such competitions are meant to be independent and may vary only in
 the threshold participation cost and range of distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i},s_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the participants.
 As scope of the presented chapter is limited to the effect of income difference
s on consumption, we discuss only a particular competition with known distributi
on of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 among a relatively small number of participants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, a few properties of a game follow where a wealth-optimising
 participant with a maximum score wins by enhancing her skills (social capital)
 and using her raw-talent.
 First, only one player with the maximum score can win a particular tournament.
 Second, the rank of the participant (rich / poor status) is of no direct
 significance part of her utility from wealth.
 Lastly, the privately known raw-talent 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and skills 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 are of no significance to expenditure decisions - which vary solely on
 the basis of rich or poor status.
 
\end_layout

