\begin_layout Standard
It is commonly argued status is a social rather than ab economic goal of
 the individual.
 Yet the difference between social and economic goals of the individual
 is hardly well-defined in either sociology or economics.
 The idea that status is orthogonal to economic goals - i.e.
 a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pure status
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 view 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moldovanuselacontestsstatus2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 - seldom fit with the real-world where status contributes to income while
 also improving with rise in income.
 Indeed the other extreme view that the economic goals alone motivate status
 competition - so that status is derived purely from economic goals is also
 unrealistic.
 As 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moldovanuselacontestsstatus2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argue, the reality is often somewhere in between the two extremes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A structural model for this interplay between economic and social goals
 is not however specified in either sociology or economics.
 The dominant view for status in both sociology and economics has been one
 based that is based on hierarchy and social deference 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990,goldthorpesociology2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This view of status in inherent in occupational status surveys widely used
 in empirical studies (e.g.
 the EGP classes or the Goldthorpe class scheme 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goldthorpesociology2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) .
 The issue with the lack of a structural model and the specific concern
 to reconcile the difference between the objective aspects of status (the
 observed reality of status differences) and its subjective aspects (the
 effect of status differences on individual behaviour) have been more widely
 discussed in sociology 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The evident issue with addressing only the objective aspect of status with
 a utilitarian model while leaving the subjective aspect exogenous is that
 status cannot be explained in economic terms when an economy for status
 is ruled out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The view of status as observed order or hierarchy is hardly an all-encompasssing
 view of status in sociology.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goode1978celebrationheroes"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, for example, discusses an economy of status while arguing that it is created
 as part of the economic processes.
 The structural issue of whether a certain social structure determines status
 judgments or the judgments themselves determine status may still remain
 unresolved in both sociology and economics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, but several limitations with the dominant hierarchy-based view of status
 have since been remarked.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The foremost contention with the hierarchy-based view of status is that
 idea of social closure often gets conflated with that of hierarchy.
 The idea of social-closure (aggregate or stÃ¤nde first discussed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "webereconomysociety1925"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) is hardly the same as social ranks that they are commonly approximated
 with in the literature (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The problem is not merely a theoretical issue.
 The subjective evaluations of status - which one is supposed to reconcile
 with the objective view - are observed to measure an overall desirability
 of occupations instead of status (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goldthorpeOccupationalGrading1975"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Skills or knowledge of individuals may seem to better predict the individual
 judgments of status (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "adlerstatuscomponents1985"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 More importantly, the scales of status that one employs in empirical studies
 are observed to vary significantly across the sections of society (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ackerwomenstratification1980"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

