\begin_layout Standard
A different perspective from the hierarchy-based view of status is one that
 relies on an interaction or a conflict at rational or normative levels.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goode1978celebrationheroes"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 , for example, argues that social institutions nurture or discourage certain
 naturally characteristics in a society.
 Thus, instead of interpreting status items as those that signal prevalent
 status norms, the dynamic view of status allows 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goode1978celebrationheroes"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to suggest that investments towards status may increase the likelihood
 of associating with higher-status members of society.
 A certain dynamism in social-groups - termed as conflict in the sociology
 literature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "webereconomysociety1925,wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

- is inherent in his view of prestige.
 While a structural model that reconciles the subjective and objective aspects
 of status are still missing from his thesis, the normative theories for
 competition among social-groups has gathered much attention in sociology
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parsonsInfluence1963,parsonssystemsocieties1971"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parsonssystemsocieties1971"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 address this issue by simply arguing the subjective and objective aspects
 to the same.
 The basic categories in terms of which we describe a system of hierarchies
 as a structure according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parsonssystemsocieties1971"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is the same as those in terms of which individual behavior or performance
 is defined.
 Thus, while culture places a premium on equality, the distribution rules
 in different social subsystems is often not aimed at generating equality.
 Much like with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goode1978celebrationheroes"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, prestige acts to assert basic importance of equality of membership status
 while making allowances for the inequalities resulting from equality of
 opportunity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The bottom line of the view is that societies must institutionalize some
 balance between equality and inequality at all times 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parsonsInfluence1963,parsonssystemsocieties1971"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

