\begin_layout Standard
Other attempts to reconcile the subjective and objective aspects of status
 (and therefore of social-closure and hierarchy) use a rational conflict
 to specify a structural basis.
 One such attempt has been through use of power as a commodity to be exchanged
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 - an approach that has drawn much criticism due to the zero-sum characteristics
 it imposes on status while treating the total status on a status society
 as fixed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wrongpower1979"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goode1978celebrationheroes"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argues, prestige is available in ample supply in society at least as a
 product of exchange processes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the current chapter, we specify a structural basis while banking on the
 Weberian framework for social-groups 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "webereconomysociety1925"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The order Weber considers in the conflict is not a hierarchy but instead
 an order of closure 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A certain dynamism in creation of closed positions of status is inherent
 in the Weberian view - one that we attempt to model with probability functions
 arising out of a priori distribution of personal attributes.
 Instead of using status as a wealth-determined goal, we follow 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "postlewaite1998socialbasisinterdeppreferences"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in considering an indirect role that status can play in maximisation of
 consumer utility from wealth.
 
\end_layout

