\begin_layout Standard
Our discussion of the effect of the threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 and the income differences 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 on participation assumes that the exogenous parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is stable with respect to short-term changes in threshold investment 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 as well as disposable incomes 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1},y_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The choices with a general intertemporally additive function 
\begin_inset Formula $u(A)$
\end_inset

 (with assets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

) for the poor and rich participants are shown in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:prisoners_dilemma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 where we define 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=\frac{\mu}{8(1-\mu)}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}=1-2p_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}'=\frac{19\mu^{2}-40\mu+20}{40(1-\mu)^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}'=1-2p_{1}'$
\end_inset

 for the three-player model discussed above.
 It's easy to see verify from Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Probability-of-winning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 that for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu<1/2$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}<1/3<p_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}'>1/3>p_{2}'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\text{Given }\mu<1/2,\text{we have}\label{eq:probability_inequality}\\
p_{1}<1/3<p_{2}\nonumber \\
p_{1}'>1/3>p_{2}'\nonumber 
\end{gather}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice the Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:prisoners_dilemma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 represents the condition when the budget is non-binding i.e.
 the poor participant is able to spend 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}<y_{1}<y_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 When the poor participant faces a binding constraint i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}<\overline{\nu}<y_{2}$
\end_inset

 , then the rich participant knows that the best case probability to win
 for the poor participant is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/3$
\end_inset

.
 The rich participant's decision to participate would depend only on utility
 from savings and the relative advantage from gain in probability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Binding-constraint"

\end_inset

Binding constraint
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming the EUT participants we first consider the simpler case of binding
 constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}<\overline{\nu}<y_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since we assume a stability in long-term participant behaviour (which itself
 is a result of observed probability of success), mixed-strategies are not
 relevant in the current set up.
 Considering pure strategies for partcipation, the rich participant would
 thus participate only when the utility from participating would be higher
 than from not participating i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(y_{2}-\overline{\nu})+\frac{p_{2}u(y_{2})+(1-p_{2})u(y_{1})}{\delta}>u(y_{2})+\frac{\frac{1}{3}u(y_{2})+\frac{2}{3}u(y_{1})}{\delta}$
\end_inset

 .
 This results in the following condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{(p_{2}-1/3)(u(y_{2})-u(y_{1}))}{\delta} & >u(y_{2})-u(y_{2}-\overline{\nu})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With income differences being the same an increase in participation cost
 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 discourages participation since RHS increases with 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\because u(y_{2}-\overline{\nu})$
\end_inset

 is decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

).
 Similarly, with participation cost 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 being the same, an increase in income-difference 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 is in the rich participant's interest to participate whereas a narrowing
 of income differences reduces incentive to participate.
 All else being the same, higher impatience (lower time-discounted value
 of money or higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

) would also discourage participation.
 Therefore, when budget is binding for the poor participant i.e.
 if the poor participant cannot participate due to 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}<\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

, then narrow income differences, higher participation costs and patience
 for savings (common for both rich and poor participants) all encourage
 the rich participant to withdraw from the game.
 This also means that wider income differences (
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

) combined with lower participation costs (
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\mu}$
\end_inset

) may together help maintain the equilibrium where only the rich participates.
 Similarly, wider income differences ( higher
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 ) and more patience for savings (higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 ) would together maintain the incentive for the rich participant to participate.
 These conclusions very much fit with the sociological observations made
 in the literature (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits,GalbraithEssential"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Non-Binding constraint
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When budget is non-binding, then participation of the rich participant is
 her dominant strategy if the condition is also 
\begin_inset Formula $u(y_{2})+\frac{u(y_{2})p_{2}'+(1-p_{2}')u(y_{1})}{\delta}<u(y_{2}-\overline{\nu})+\frac{\frac{1}{3}u(y_{2})+\frac{2}{3}u(y_{1})}{\delta})$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{(1/3-p_{2}')(u(y_{2})-u(y_{1}))}{\delta} & >u(y_{2})-u(y_{2}-\overline{\nu})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inferences on how 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 influence the participation (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Binding-constraint"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) remain the same for the above condition.
 We now consider the conditions for all possible Nash equilibria in the
 current set up.
 For ease of notation we define the following for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu},y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U_{1} & \equiv u(y_{1})-u(y_{1}-\overline{\nu})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U_{2} & \equiv u(y_{2})-u(y_{2}-\overline{\nu})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

